# Migrate the Claude Code config to @TOOL@

The canonical Claude Code artifacts are at `@CLAUDE_SRC@` (skills,
commands, helper scripts, CLAUDE.md). A deterministic converter exists
at `@AI_DIR@/convert/` with a per-tool adapter
`@AI_DIR@/convert/adapters/@TOOL@.py`.

Current locally observed `@TOOL@` version: `@CURRENT_TOOL_VERSION@`
Last recorded tested version: `@RECORDED_TESTED_VERSION@`
Version stamp file: `@STAMP_PATH@`

Your job:

1. Read the @TOOL@ adapter and judge whether it is correct and current
   against @TOOL@'s present-day config format and paths.
2. If the locally observed version is the same as, or approximately the
   same as, the recorded tested version, you may take the fast path for
   speed: run the mechanical converter/scripts first, then inspect the
   result and patch only what drifted. If the versions are materially
   different, inspect more carefully before trusting the scripts.
3. If the adapter is sound, run it: `cd @AI_DIR@ && python3 -m
   convert.convert --tool @TOOL@`.
4. If it is stale or wrong, **patch the adapter in place**
   (`@AI_DIR@/convert/adapters/@TOOL@.py`) so it is correct, then run
   it. The repair persists for every future run, including Mode 1.
   Leave the edits in the working tree for the user to review and
   commit — do not commit them yourself.
5. Set up any non-converted, tool-native local config that the converter
   skips (for example MCP servers and other assistant-specific user
   settings). Follow any tool-specific guidance below when present.
6. After the migration is verified, update `@STAMP_PATH@` so it records
   the exact version string you successfully tested against. Preserve the
   `tool:` line, set `tested-version:` to the validated version, and set
   `status: verified`.
7. Verify the result and report what you ran, patched, stamped, and set up.

@TOOL_EXTRA_GUIDANCE@

Do not edit files under `@CLAUDE_SRC@` — that is the Claude Code source
of truth.
